    thinking: "**Defining Initial UI Elements**\n\nOkay, I\'ve started thinking about `src/App.tsx`. The core focus is a single-page app with a greeting card. I\'m visualizing a design that heavily utilizes negative space to draw attention to the central element. The initial idea is to display a prominent heading, either \"Hello, World!\" or a personalized greeting, depending on user input.\n\n\n**Refining Input Field & Clock**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the input field and the real-time clock. I\'m aiming for clean styling with padding, icons from `lucide-react`, and proper state management. I need to make it feel pristine. The clock, showing either local or UTC time in JetBrains Mono font, will ground the greeting. The time is `2026-06-22T19:12:44-07:00`, so I\'ll be implementing that clean, updating element.\n\n\n\n**Simplifying & Structuring Design**\n\nI\'m now focusing on simplicity to avoid over-engineering, especially the \"Reset\" button for the name field, ensuring a clean transition. I was about to add multiple themes, but I caught myself! The guidelines are clear: one polished, distinctive light theme only. Now, I\'m structuring `/src/App.tsx`, envisioning a centered greeting card with full viewport height using flexbox. The header will feature a real-time clock in monospace.\n\n\n**Clarifying System Details**\n\nI\'m now revising the design guidelines to ensure the system details are not displayed in the final interface. Specifically, the real-time clock should display just the current time, with the option of also showing the date, not any system metadata. I\'m prioritizing human-centered design principles.\nI\'m also setting up the main section and input area using Space Grotesk and mono fonts.\n\n\n**Designing Dynamic Interaction**\n\nI\'m now focusing on interactive elements, specifically the dynamic subtitle and card container. I\'m exploring how the subtitle changes based on input, providing different messages depending on user input. I\'m prioritizing accessibility and visual appeal with the card container, making sure it has good contrast and proper alignment. I\'m implementing a responsive design. I\'m working with React, motion, and Tailwind CSS.\n\n\n**Verifying Framework Imports**\n\nI\'m now verifying import statements. I\'ve confirmed `motion` comes from `motion/react` as the guidelines require. I\'ll utilize `lucide-react` for simple decorative icons, as the design system specifies, to maintain code quality. I\'ll start with a Sparkles icon. Now, I\'m ready to write excellent code in `src/App.tsx`.\n\n\n**Confirming Unique IDs**\n\nI\'m now implementing the `id` attributes for all interactive and container elements. I\'ve listed them to ensure compliance. I\'m focusing on the main app wrapper, greeting card, header, clock widget, main heading, and input container. I\'ll make sure the input field itself has a relevant ID. I\'ll write the code that generates all the HTML elements now.\n\n\n"
